Title: Anemia

Overview:
- Anemia is a condition in which the body does not have enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to tissues.
- It commonly occurs due to low levels of hemoglobin or iron deficiency.
- Anemia can be mild or severe and may develop gradually over time.
- It affects people of all ages, especially women and children.
- Proper nutrition and early detection are important for effective management.

Common Symptoms:
- Persistent fatigue or feeling tired easily.
- Weakness and low energy levels.
- Pale or yellowish skin.
- Shortness of breath during physical activity.
- Dizziness or lightheadedness.
- Cold hands and feet.
- Headaches or difficulty concentrating.
- Rapid or irregular heartbeat in severe cases.

Risk Factors:
- Poor diet lacking iron, vitamin B12, or folic acid.
- Blood loss due to injury, menstruation, or internal bleeding.
- Chronic diseases affecting nutrient absorption.
- Pregnancy increasing nutritional demand.
- Genetic conditions affecting red blood cells.
- Frequent infections or weakened immune system.
- Poor overall health and nutrition.

Basic Home Diagnosis (Preliminary Checks):
- Observe signs like fatigue, pale skin, and weakness.
- Check for shortness of breath during normal activities.
- Monitor dizziness or frequent headaches.
- Look at nail beds or inner eyelids for paleness.
- Track energy levels and daily activity tolerance.
- Note any recent blood loss or poor dietary intake.
- If symptoms persist, get a blood test (hemoglobin level) for confirmation.

Management and Prevention:
- Eat iron-rich foods such as leafy greens, beans, lentils, and meat.
- Include foods rich in vitamin B12 and folic acid.
- Maintain a balanced and nutritious diet.
- Take iron supplements only if prescribed by a doctor.
- Avoid skipping meals and maintain regular eating habits.
- Stay hydrated and maintain overall health.
- Treat underlying causes such as infections or chronic diseases.
- Regular health checkups to monitor hemoglobin levels.

When to Seek Medical Help:
- Severe fatigue affecting daily life.
- Shortness of breath even at rest.
- Rapid or irregular heartbeat.
- Persistent dizziness or fainting.
- Very pale skin or worsening symptoms.
- Suspected internal bleeding or heavy blood loss.

